📌 Event Capturing in JavaScript
📖 What is Event Capturing?

Event Capturing (also called Trickling) is the phase where an event starts from the top of the DOM tree and travels downward to the target element.

In simple words:

The event moves from parent → child before reaching the actual clicked element.

🌳 How It Works (Conceptual Flow)

If we have this structure:

<div id="parent">
  <button id="child">Click Me</button>
</div>

When the button is clicked, during capturing phase, the event flows like this:

document

<html>

<body>

<div id="parent">

<button id="child"> (target)

This downward movement is called Event Capturing.

🧠 Event Flow in JavaScript (Complete Order)

Every DOM event has three phases:

Capturing Phase (Top → Target) ⬇️

Target Phase

Bubbling Phase (Target → Top) ⬆️

By default, JavaScript event listeners work in the bubbling phase, not capturing.

🔧 How to Enable Event Capturing

To use capturing, you must explicitly enable it:

element.addEventListener("click", handlerFunction, true);

or

element.addEventListener("click", handlerFunction, { capture: true });

The third parameter true enables capturing phase.

📌 Example
document.getElementById("parent").addEventListener("click", function() {
  console.log("Parent clicked (Capturing)");
}, true);

document.getElementById("child").addEventListener("click", function() {
  console.log("Child clicked");
});

When clicking the button, output will be:

Parent clicked (Capturing)
Child clicked

Because capturing runs before bubbling.

🛑 Stop Capturing

You can stop propagation in capturing phase also using:

event.stopPropagation();

This stops the event from continuing further.

🚀 Why Event Capturing is Useful?

Useful when you want parent logic to run before child logic

Helps control event flow precisely

Important in advanced UI handling scenarios

✅ Summary

Event flows from top → target

Not enabled by default

Enabled using { capture: true }

Runs before bubbling phase

Can be stopped using stopPropagation()